# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: resource-hints
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] The **`rel`** attribute defines the relationship between a linked resource and the current document.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Valid on `<link>`, `<a>`, `<area>`, and `<form>`, the supported values depend on the element on which the attribute is found.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] The type of relationships is given by the value of the `rel` attribute, which, if present, must have a value that is an unordered set of unique space-separated keywords.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Differently from a `class` name, which does not express semantics, the `rel` attribute must express tokens that are semantically valid for both machines and humans.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] The current registries for the possible values of the `rel` attribute are the IANA link relation registry, the HTML Living Standard, and the freely-editable existing-rel-values page in the microformats wiki, as suggested by the Living Standard.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] If a `rel` attribute not present in one of the three sources above is used some HTML validators (such as the W3C Markup Validation Service) will generate a warning.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] The following table lists some of the most important existing keywords.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Every keyword within a space-separated value should be unique within that value.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] The `rel` attribute is relevant to the `<link>`, `<a>`, `<area>`, and `<form>` elements, but some values only relevant to a subset of those elements.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Like all HTML keyword attribute values, these values are case-insensitive.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] The `rel` attribute has no default value.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] If the attribute is omitted or if none of the values in the attribute are supported, then the document has no particular relationship with the destination resource other than there being a hyperlink between the two.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] In this case, on `<link>` and `<form>`, if the `rel` attribute is absent, has no keywords, or if not one or more of the space-separated keywords above, then the element does not create any links.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] `<a>` and `<area>` will still created links, but without a defined relationship.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Indicates an alternate representation of the current document.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Valid for `<link>`, `<a>`, and `<area>`, the meaning depends on the values of the other attributes.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Indicates the referenced document provides further information about the author of the current document or article.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] With `<a>` and `<area>`, it indicates the linked document (or `mailto:`) provides information about the author of the nearest `<article>` ancestor if there is one, otherwise the entire document.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] With `<link>`, it represents the author of the entire document.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Relevant as the `rel` attribute value for the `<a>` and `<area>` elements.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Gives a permalink for the nearest ancestor `<article>` element, if there is one.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] If there is no ancestor `<article>` element, gives a permalink for the section the linking element is most closely associated with.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Valid for `<link>`, it defines the preferred URL for the current document, which helps search engines reduce duplicate content.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Valid for `<link>`, it defines a compression dictionary that can be used to compress future downloads for resources on this site so the download sizes of those resources are smaller than standard compression.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Relevant for the `<link>` element both in the `<body>` and `<head>`, it tells the browser to preemptively perform DNS resolution for the target resource's origin.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Useful for resources the user will likely need, it helps reduce latency and thereby improves performance when the user does access the resources as the browser preemptively performed DNS resolution for the origin of the specified resource.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] See dns-prefetch described in resource hints.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Relevant to `<form>`, `<a>`, and `<area>`, it indicates the referenced document is not part of the current site.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] This can be used with attribute selectors to style external links in a way that indicates to the user that they will be leaving the current site.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Allows the page to be render-blocked until the essential parts of the document are parsed so it will render consistently.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Note that render-blocking occurs only when supplemented with the `blocking="render"` attribute.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Relevant to `<form>`, `<link>`, `<a>`, and `<area>`, the `help` keyword indicates that the linked to content provides context-sensitive help, providing information for the parent of the element defining the hyperlink, and its children.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] When used within `<link>`, the help is for the whole document.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] When included with `<a>` and `<area>` and supported, the default `cursor` will be `help` instead of `pointer`.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Valid with `<link>`, the linked resource represents the icon, a resource for representing the page in the user interface, for the current document.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] If there are multiple `<link rel="icon">`s, the browser uses their `media`, `type`, and `sizes` attributes to select the most appropriate icon.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] If several icons are equally appropriate, the last one is used.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] If the most appropriate icon is later found to be inappropriate, for example because it uses an unsupported format, the browser proceeds to the next-most appropriate, and so on.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Valid on the `<a>`, `<area>`, `<form>`, `<link>` elements, the `license` value indicates that the hyperlink leads to a document describing the licensing information; that the main content of the current document is covered by the copyright license described by the referenced document.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] If not inside the `<head>` element, the standard doesn't distinguish between a hyperlink applying to a specific part of the document or to the document as a whole.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Only the data on the page can indicate this.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Requires the use of the CORS protocol for cross-origin fetching.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Useful for improved performance, and relevant to the `<link>` anywhere in the document, setting `rel="modulepreload"` tells the browser to preemptively fetch the script (and dependencies) and store it in the document's module map for later evaluation.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] `modulepreload` links can ensure network fetching is done with the module ready (but not evaluated) in the module map before it is necessarily needed.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Relevant to `<form>`, `<link>`, `<a>`, and `<area>`, the `next` values indicates that the current document is a part of a series, and that the next document in the series is the referenced document.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] When included in a `<link>`, browsers may assume that document will be fetched next, and treat it as a resource hint.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Relevant to `<form>`, `<a>`, and `<area>`, the `nofollow` keyword tells search engine spiders to ignore the link relationship.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] The nofollow relationship may indicate the current document's owner does not endorse the referenced document.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] It is often included by Search Engine Optimizers pretending their link farms are not spam pages.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Relevant to `<form>`, `<a>`, and `<area>`, creates a top-level browsing context that is not an auxiliary browsing context if the hyperlink would create either of those to begin with (i.e., has an appropriate `target` attribute value).
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] In other words, it makes the link behave as if `window.opener` were null and `target="_parent"` were set.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Relevant to `<form>`, `<a>`, and `<area>`, including this value makes the referrer unknown (no `Referer` header will be included), and creates a top-level browsing context as if `noopener` were also set.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Creates an auxiliary browsing context if the hyperlink would otherwise create a top-level browsing context that is not an auxiliary browsing context (i.e., has `"_blank"` as `target` attribute value).
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Gives the address of the pingback server that handles pingbacks to the current document.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Provides a hint to the browser suggesting that it open a connection to the linked website in advance, without disclosing any private information or downloading any content, so that when the link is followed the linked content can be fetched more quickly.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Specifies that the user agent should preemptively fetch and cache the target resource as it is likely to be required for a followup navigation.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Specifies that the user agent must preemptively fetch and cache the target resource for current navigation according to the potential destination given by the `as` attribute (and the priority associated with the corresponding destination).
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Specifies that the user agent should preemptively fetch the target resource and process it in a way that helps deliver a faster response in the future, for example by fetching its subresources or performing some rendering.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] This feature is superseded by the Speculation Rules API.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Similar to the `next` keyword, relevant to `<form>`, `<link>`, `<a>`, and `<area>`, the `prev` values indicates that the current document is a part of a series, and that the link references a previous document in the series is the referenced document.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Note: The synonym `previous` is incorrect and should not be used.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Valid for `<a>`, `<area>`, and `<link>` elements, the `privacy-policy` value indicates that the referenced document is the Privacy Policy which describes the data collection and usage practices of the current document.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Relevant to `<form>`, `<link>`, `<a>`, and `<area>` elements, the `search` keywords indicates that the hyperlink references a document whose interface is specially designed for searching in the current document, site, and related resources, providing a link to a resource that can be used to search.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] If the `type` attribute is set to `application/opensearchdescription+xml` the resource is an OpenSearch plugin that can be easily added to the interface of Firefox.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Valid for the `<link>` element, it imports an external resource to be used as a stylesheet.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] The `type` attribute is not needed if it's a `text/css` stylesheet, as that is the default value.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] If it's not a stylesheet of type `text/css` it is best to declare the type.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] While this attribute defines the link as being a stylesheet, the interaction with other attributes and other key terms within the rel value impact whether the stylesheet is downloaded and/or used.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] When used with the `alternate` keyword, it defines an alternative style sheet.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] In this case, include a non-empty `title`.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] The external stylesheet will not be used or even downloaded if the media does not match the value of the `media` attribute.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Valid for the `<a>`, and `<area>` elements, it gives a tag (identified by the given address) that applies to the current document.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] The tag value denotes that the link refers to a document describing a tag applying to the document on which it is located.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] This link type is not meant for tags within a tag cloud, as those tags apply to a group of pages, whereas the `tag` value of the `rel` attribute is for a single document.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Valid for `<a>`, `<area>`, and `<link>` elements, the `terms-of-service` value indicates that the referenced document is the Terms of Service that describes the agreements between the current document's provider and users who wish to use the document provided.
[src:resource-hints/attributes-rel] Specifies the icon for a web application on an iOS device.
[src:resource-hints/dns-prefetch] Since September 2025, this feature works across the latest devices and browser versions.
[src:resource-hints/dns-prefetch] This feature might not work in older devices or browsers.
[src:resource-hints/dns-prefetch] See Using dns-prefetch for more details.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] The **`<link>`** HTML element specifies relationships between the current document and an external resource.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] This element is most commonly used to link to stylesheets, but is also used to establish site icons (both "favicon" style icons and icons for the home screen and apps on mobile devices) among other things.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] This example provides the path to the stylesheet inside an `href` attribute and a `rel` attribute with a value of `stylesheet`.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] The `rel` stands for "relationship", and is one of the key features of the `<link>` element — the value denotes how the item being linked to is related to the containing document.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] There are a number of other common types you'll come across.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] The `sizes` attribute indicates the icon size, while the `type` contains the MIME type of the resource being linked.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] These provide useful hints to allow the browser to choose the most appropriate icon available.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] You can also provide a media type or query inside a `media` attribute; this resource will then only be loaded if the media condition is true.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] Some interesting new performance and security features have been added to the `<link>` element too.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] A `rel` value of `preload` indicates that the browser should preload this resource (see `rel="preload"` for more details), with the `as` attribute indicating the specific class of content being fetched.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] The `crossorigin` attribute indicates whether the resource should be fetched with a CORS request.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] This element includes the global attributes.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] This attribute is required when `rel="preload"` has been set on the `<link>` element, optional when `rel="modulepreload"` has been set, and otherwise should not be used.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] It specifies the type of content being loaded by the `<link>`, which is necessary for request matching, application of correct content security policy, and setting of correct `Accept` request header.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] Furthermore, `rel="preload"` uses this as a signal for request prioritization.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] The table below lists the valid values for this attribute and the elements or resources they apply to.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] This attribute explicitly indicates that certain operations should be blocked until specific conditions are met.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] It must only be used when the `rel` attribute contains the `expect` or `stylesheet` keywords.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] With `rel="expect"`, it indicates that operations should be blocked until a specific DOM node has been parsed.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] With `rel="stylesheet"`, it indicates that operations should be blocked until an external stylesheet and its critical subresources have been fetched and applied to the document.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] The operations that are to be blocked must be a space-separated list of blocking tokens listed below.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] This enumerated attribute indicates whether CORS must be used when fetching the resource.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] CORS-enabled images can be reused in the `<canvas>` element without being *tainted*.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] A cross-origin request (i.e., with an `Origin` HTTP header) is performed, but no credential is sent (i.e., no cookie, X.509 certificate, or HTTP Basic authentication).
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] If the server does not give credentials to the origin site (by not setting the `Access-Control-Allow-Origin` HTTP header) the resource will be tainted and its usage restricted.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] A cross-origin request (i.e., with an `Origin` HTTP header) is performed along with a credential sent (i.e., a cookie, certificate, and/or HTTP Basic authentication is performed).
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] If the server does not give credentials to the origin site (through `Access-Control-Allow-Credentials` HTTP header), the resource will be *tainted* and its usage restricted.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] If the attribute is not present, the resource is fetched without a CORS request (i.e., without sending the `Origin` HTTP header), preventing its non-tainted usage.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] If invalid, it is handled as if the enumerated keyword **anonymous** was used.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] See CORS settings attributes for additional information.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] For `rel="stylesheet"` only, the `disabled` Boolean attribute indicates whether the described stylesheet should be loaded and applied to the document.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] If `disabled` is specified in the HTML when it is loaded, the stylesheet will not be loaded during page load.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] Instead, the stylesheet will be loaded on-demand, if and when the `disabled` attribute is changed to `false` or removed.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] Setting the `disabled` property in the DOM causes the stylesheet to be removed from the document's `Document.styleSheets` list.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] Provides a hint of the relative priority to use when fetching a resource of a particular type.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] Fetch the resource at a high priority relative to other resources of the same type.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] Fetch the resource at a low priority relative to other resources of the same type.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] Don't set a preference for the fetch priority.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] It is used if no value or an invalid value is set.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] This attribute specifies the URL of the linked resource.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] This attribute indicates the language of the linked resource.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] Values should be valid BCP 47 language tags.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] Use this attribute only if the `href` attribute is present.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] For `rel="preload"` and `as="image"` only, the `imagesizes` attribute has similar syntax and semantics as the `sizes` attribute that indicates to preload the appropriate resource used by an `img` element with corresponding values for its `srcset` and `sizes` attributes.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] For `rel="preload"` and `as="image"` only, the `imagesrcset` attribute has similar syntax and semantics as the `srcset` attribute that indicates to preload the appropriate resource used by an `img` element with corresponding values for its `srcset` and `sizes` attributes.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] This attribute contains one or more hashes of the resource.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] It is used to ensure that the content of the resource is what the developer expects it to be, and has not been replaced with a malicious copy in a supply chain attack.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] The attribute must only be specified when the `rel` attribute is set to `stylesheet`, `preload`, or `modulepreload`.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] This attribute specifies the media that the linked resource applies to.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] Its value must be a media type / media query.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] This attribute is mainly useful when linking to external stylesheets — it allows the user agent to pick the best adapted one for the device it runs on.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] A string indicating which referrer to use when fetching the resource.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] For detailed explanations and examples of each policy, see the `Referrer-Policy` header documentation.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] This attribute names a relationship of the linked document to the current document.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] The attribute must be a space-separated list of link type values.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] This attribute defines the sizes of the icons for visual media contained in the resource.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] It must be present only if the `rel` contains a value of `icon` or a non-standard type such as Apple's `apple-touch-icon`.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] The `title` attribute has special semantics on the `<link>` element.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] When used on a `<link rel="stylesheet">` it defines a default or an alternate stylesheet.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] This attribute is used to define the type of the content linked to.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] The value of the attribute should be a MIME type such as **text/html**, **text/css**, and so on.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] The common use of this attribute is to define the type of stylesheet being referenced (such as **text/css**), but given that CSS is the only stylesheet language used on the web, not only is it possible to omit the `type` attribute, but is actually now recommended practice.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] It is also used on `rel="preload"` link types, to make sure the browser only downloads file types that it supports.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] Defines the frame or window name that has the defined linking relationship or that will show the rendering of any linked resource.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] This attribute defines the character encoding of the linked resource.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] The value is a space- and/or comma-delimited list of character sets as defined in RFC 2045.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] The value of this attribute shows the relationship of the current document to the linked document, as defined by the `href` attribute.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] The attribute thus defines the reverse relationship compared to the value of the `rel` attribute.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] Link type values for the attribute are similar to the possible values for `rel`.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] You can also specify alternative style sheets.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] The user can choose which style sheet to use by choosing it from the **View > Page Style** menu.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] This provides a way for users to see multiple versions of a page.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] You can include links to several icons on the same page, and the browser will choose which one works best for its particular context using the `rel` and `sizes` values as hints.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] For information about what `sizes` to choose for Apple icons, see Apple's documentation on configuring web applications and the referenced Apple human interface guidelines.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] Usually, it is sufficient to provide a large image, such as 192x192, and let the browser scale it down as needed, but you may want to provide images with different levels of detail for different sizes, as the Apple design guideline recommends.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] Providing smaller icons for lower resolutions also saves bandwidth.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] It may not be necessary to provide `<link>` elements at all.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] For example, browsers automatically request `/favicon.ico` from the root of a site, and Apple also automatically requests `/apple-touch-icon-[size].png`, `/apple-touch-icon.png`, etc.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] However, providing explicit links protects you against changes to these conventions.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] You can provide a media type or query inside a `media` attribute; this resource will then only be loaded if the media condition is true.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] You can find a number of `<link rel="preload">` examples in Preloading content with `rel="preload"`.
[src:resource-hints/elements-link] You can include `render` token inside a `blocking` attribute; the rendering of the page will be blocked till the resource and its critical subresources are fetched and applied to the document.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preconnect] It’s been available across browsers since January 2020.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preconnect] The **`preconnect`** keyword for the `rel` attribute of the `<link>` element is a hint to browsers that the user is likely to need resources from the target resource's origin, and therefore the browser can likely improve the user experience by preemptively initiating a connection to that origin.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preconnect] Preconnecting speeds up future loads from a given origin by preemptively performing part or all of the handshake (DNS+TCP for HTTP, and DNS+TCP+TLS for HTTPS origins).
[src:resource-hints/rel-preconnect] `<link rel="preconnect">` will provide a benefit to any future cross-origin HTTP request, navigation or subresource.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preconnect] It has no benefit on same-origin requests because the connection is already open.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preconnect] If a page needs to make connections to many third-party domains, preconnecting them all can be counterproductive.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preconnect] The `<link rel="preconnect">` hint is best used for only the most critical connections.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preconnect] For the others, just use `<link rel="dns-prefetch">` to save time on the first step — the DNS lookup.
[src:resource-hints/rel-prefetch] This feature is not Baseline because it does not work in some of the most widely-used browsers.
[src:resource-hints/rel-prefetch] The **`prefetch`** keyword for the `rel` attribute of the `<link>` element provides a hint to browsers that the user is likely to need the target resource for future navigations, and therefore the browser can likely improve the user experience by preemptively fetching and caching the resource.
[src:resource-hints/rel-prefetch] `<link rel="prefetch">` is used for same-site navigation resources, or for subresources used by same-site pages.
[src:resource-hints/rel-prefetch] The result is kept in the HTTP cache on disk.
[src:resource-hints/rel-prefetch] Because of this it is useful for prefetching subresources, even if they are not used by the current page.
[src:resource-hints/rel-prefetch] You could also use it to prefetch the next document the user will likely visit on the site.
[src:resource-hints/rel-prefetch] However, as a result you need to be careful with headers — for example certain Cache-Control headers could block prefetching (for example `no-cache` or `no-store`).
[src:resource-hints/rel-prefetch] `<link rel="prefetch">` is functionally equivalent to a `fetch()` call with a `priority: "low"` option set on it, except that the former will generally have an even lower priority, and it will have a `Sec-Purpose: prefetch` header set on the request.
[src:resource-hints/rel-prefetch] Note that in general browsers will give prefetch resources a lower priority than preload ones (e.g., requested via `<link rel="preload">`) — the current page is more important than the next.
[src:resource-hints/rel-prefetch] The fetch request for a `prefetch` operation results in an HTTP request that includes the HTTP header `Sec-Purpose: prefetch`.
[src:resource-hints/rel-prefetch] A server might use this header to change the cache timeouts for the resources, or perform other special handling.
[src:resource-hints/rel-prefetch] The request will also include the `Sec-Fetch-Dest` header with the value set to `empty`.
[src:resource-hints/rel-prefetch] The `Accept` header in the request will match the value used for normal navigation requests.
[src:resource-hints/rel-prefetch] This allows the browser to find the matching cached resources following navigation.
[src:resource-hints/rel-prefetch] Prefetching can be used to fetch both HTML and sub-resources for a possible next navigation.
[src:resource-hints/rel-prefetch] A common use case is to have a website landing page that fetches more "heavy-weight" resources used by the rest of the site.
[src:resource-hints/rel-prefetch] Many browsers now implement some form of cache partitioning, which makes `<link rel="prefetch">` useless for resources intended for use by different top-level sites.
[src:resource-hints/rel-prefetch] This includes the main document when navigating cross-site.
[src:resource-hints/rel-prefetch] Would not be accessible from `https://aggregator.example/`.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] It’s been available across browsers since January 2021.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] The `preload` value of the `<link>` element's `rel` attribute lets you declare fetch requests in the HTML's `<head>`, specifying resources that your page will need very soon, which you want to start loading early in the page lifecycle, before browsers' main rendering machinery kicks in.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] This ensures they are available earlier and are less likely to block the page's render, improving performance.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] Even though the name contains the term *load*, it doesn't load and execute the script but only schedules it to be downloaded and cached with a higher priority.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] Here however, we will use a `rel` value of `preload`, which turns `<link>` into a preloader for any resource we want.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] Here we preload our CSS and JavaScript files so they will be available as soon as they are required for the rendering of the page later on.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] This example is trivial, as the browser probably discovers the `<link rel="stylesheet">` and `<script>` elements in the same chunk of HTML as the preloads, but the benefits can be seen much more clearly the later resources are discovered and the larger they are.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] `<link>` elements can accept a `type` attribute, which contains the MIME type of the resource the element points to.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] This is especially useful when preloading resources — the browser will use the `type` attribute value to work out if it supports that resource, and will only download it if so, ignoring it if not.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] The code in the example above causes the `image/avif` image to be preloaded only in supporting browsers — and for users who have `image/avif` support in their browsers, causes the `image/avif` image to actually be used (since it's the first `<source>` specified).
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] That makes the image download hopefully smaller for users who have `image/avif` support in their browsers.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] Therefore, specifying preloading for multiple types of the same resource is discouraged.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] Instead, the best practice is to specify preloading only for the type the majority of your users are likely to actually use.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] That's why the code in the example above doesn't specify preloading for the `image/webp` image.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] When preloading resources that are fetched with CORS enabled (e.g., `fetch()`, `XMLHttpRequest` or fonts), special care needs to be taken to setting the `crossorigin` attribute on your `<link>` element.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] The attribute needs to be set to match the resource's CORS and credentials mode, even when the fetch is not cross-origin.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] As mentioned above, one interesting case where this applies is font files.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] Because of various reasons, these have to be fetched using anonymous-mode CORS (see Font fetching requirements).
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] Not only are we providing the MIME type hints in the `type` attributes, but we are also providing the `crossorigin` attribute to make sure the preload's CORS mode matches the eventual font resource request.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] One nice feature of `<link>` elements is their ability to accept `media` attributes.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] These can accept media types or full-blown media queries, allowing you to do responsive preloading!
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] We include `media` attributes on our `<link>` elements so that a narrow image is preloaded if the user has a narrow viewport, and a wider image is loaded if they have a wide viewport.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] We use `Window.matchMedia` / `MediaQueryList` to do this (see Testing media queries for more).
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] This same technique also applies to other resource types.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] For example, when used with fonts, preloading makes it more likely the font will be available at render time, reducing the chance of a flash of unstyled text (FOUT).
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] This doesn't have to be limited to images, or even files of the same type — think big!
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] You could perhaps preload and display a simplified SVG diagram if the user is on a narrow screen where bandwidth and CPU is potentially more limited, or preload a complex chunk of JavaScript then use it to render an interactive 3D model if the user's resources are more plentiful.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] Another nice thing about these preloads is that you can execute them with script.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] This means that the browser will preload the `myscript.js` file, but not actually use it yet.
[src:resource-hints/rel-preload] This is useful when you want to preload a script, but then defer execution until exactly when you need it.
